- Sun 14 Jul 2019
From: Daniel Lucey <daniel.lucey8@gmail.com> [abridged, edited]
[Daniel Lucey, senior scholar with the O'Neill Institute for National and Global Health Law and an adjunct professor of medicine-infectious diseases at Georgetown University Medical Center]

"The official DRC MoH 5-paragraph report about the Goma patient from Dr Tedros's twitter feed: the pastor became symptomatic 9 Jul 2019 in Butembo, then got on the bus 12 Jul 2019 and travelled with 18 other passengers to Goma, arriving [Sun 14 Jul 2019. He was known to be ill, although NOT due to Ebola until he arrived today in Goma. He was first taken to a "centre de sante" [health center] where the medical workers first suspected Ebola and transferred him to an ETU [Ebola treatment unit] where his lab test for Ebola was performed and around 3pm ("vers 15h") confirmed EVD. The bus driver and 18 other passengers have reportedly been identified and will be vaccinated starting tomorrow [Mon 15 Jul 2019]."

"If my translation from the French and all this information is accurate, then in my opinion there is no reason to start vaccinating people in Goma with the J&J vaccine. The main point of the BBC interview [BBC Radio 'World Service Newsday programme' interview broadcast at 22:30 EDT 15 Jul 2019] that I emphasized was what IHR-mandated "temporary recommendations" Dr Tedros could announce immediately after declaring a PHEIC. (For example, (1) improved safety and security measures; (2) extending healthcare to "Ebola and Beyond" such as, malaria, diarrheal diseases, maternal and child health, measles vaccination; and (3) warning against unintended and adverse effects of declaring a PHEIC, for example that if airlines stop flying to DRC they will be publicly called out by the WHO D-G and other measures taken to dissuade such behaviors that would have an adverse effect on DRC travel and trade (and maybe hinder the NGO "Ebola fighters" efforts from transporting workers and materials into DRC).

Also, tomorrow [15 Jul 2019] in Geneva a large and public Ebola meeting with multiple esteemed people and organizations will be held at 13:00 their time. [See report below]. I anticipate an announcement about the DRC/WHO/Partners Ebola "4th Strategic Response Plan" that will cover the next 5-6 months of the epidemic. Ideally I hoped some of the recommendations to be announced as part of this 4th Strategic Response Plan would be adapted/adopted into PHEIC "temporary recommendations"; however, now I do not anticipate declaration of a PHEIC tomorrow. Instead, I expect a statement regarding why a PHEIC is not being declared. Events seem to be accelerating."

[This incursion into Goma by Ebola virus could be a "turning point" as pointed out by others, or the preparation in place for exactly this event could allow it to be controlled without further spread. Those of us on the sidelines will have to hold our breath and wait and see which way it goes. The Washington Post Op-Ed piece written by Ronald A Klain and Daniel Lucey, could not have been more timely [see ProMED-mail Ebola update (65): Congo DR (NK, IT) case update, summaries, opinion 20190713.6566907]. Even if we are lucky this time and Ebola is contained before it spreads further into Goma, it is time for the global community to take stock of the situation and take action to not only control Ebola, but also measles, TB, malaria, and the other neglected diseases afflicting this population before things get even worse.

For related but overlapping articles see:
https://www.statnews.com/2019/07/14/congo-confirms-first-ebola-case-goma/ and
https://us.cnn.com/2019/07/14/health/ebola-outbreak-goma-drc/index.html
- Mod.LK]

